The students, Brianna Hawk and Kayla 
Martinez, said they merely hoped to promote awareness of the disease at 
their middle school. They filed suit when they were suspended for 
defying the ban on their school's Breast Cancer Awareness Day.

In
August, the 3rd US Circuit Court of Appeals upheld a lower court's 
decision in favor of the girls, saying also that the district didn't 
prove the bracelets are disruptive.

Superintendent John Reinhart told The Express-Times of Easton he supports the board's decision.

'The
Third Circuit Court has compromised administrators' abilities to 
intervene in what is and what is not appropriate in school,' he said.

In court sessions, Reinhart had called the bracelets 'cause-based marketing energized by sexual double-entendres.'

An
attorney for the American Civil Liberties Union, which helped the girls
challenge the rule, said Tuesday night the school had been hinting that
it would petition the Supreme Court.

